Access has many dimensions and implies four facets: Affordability (Can I pay for it?), availability (Is it available near me?), acceptability (Does the formulation meet my needs) and adequacy (Does the healthcare system meet my expectation?)
Assuming that sufficient studies have been done to understand the acceptability of the Covid-19 vaccines among African populations and that there is enough manufacturing capacity to provide Kenyans with adequate doses of the vaccines, the issue of affordability sticks out like a sore thumb. This is the principle that governments and policymakers will grapple with now and in the coming days.





Developing countries should take advantage of exemptions in the World Trade Organization’s (WHO) Trade-related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights, or Trips — namely, compulsory licensing and parallel importation.
With compulsory licensing, a country can suspend the patent holder’s right to market exclusivity and manufacture a product within its jurisdiction to expand access to the medicine, especially in public health emergencies.
Technology
To avoid the inevitable confrontation with pharmaceutical companies, some countries ask patent holders to allow local firms to make the same medicines or technologies under licence. Parallel importation seeks to take advantage of differences in prices of a medicine or technology in different markets.



