Pharmaceuticals segment markets based on many factors, key among them the ability of a population to pay a certain price for a product.
For instance, because of the low cost of production in South Asia, a drug from India may be several times cheaper than the same one made in Europe or Kenya.
But countries that have tried to use compulsory licensing and parallel importation have had their arms twisted by developed countries, where the big pharmaceuticals are influential and substantial taxpayers. Such was the case in South Africa in efforts to bring down the cost of patented HIV/Aids drugs.
Countries have come together as a bloc to move a certain volume of commodities and negotiate better prices. WHO has made efforts to have this in place for Covid-19 vaccines for developing countries.
International organisations such the Clinton Health Access Initiative (CHAI) and UNITAID, an international drug purchasing facility, have also intervened further upstream by directly negotiating with manufacturers to bring down the price of essential medicines and health technologies.
Kenya needs such tools in its arsenal to make essential medicines and health technologies more affordable to all, both in the public and private sector.



